### Timing

* Total dwell time on the joint: typically **2–4 seconds**
* Too short → incomplete wetting, cold joint
* Too long → component damage, lifted pads, burned flux

<div class="nav-bar">[[← Previous->Tinning the Tip]] [[Next: Reading the Joint →->Reading the Joint]]</div>


:: Common Mistakes {"position":"275,150","size":"100,100"}
<div class="slide-label">Slide 11 of 14</div>

## Common Mistakes

* **Heating the solder instead of the joint**: solder balls up on the tip instead of flowing into the joint
* **Moving the joint during cooling**: creates a cold, electrically unreliable connection
* **Too much solder**: blobs are hard to inspect and can cause bridges
* **Too little heat time**: solder doesn't wet; looks complete but is intermittent
* **Oxidized or dirty tip**: heat won't transfer; joints look lumpy regardless of technique
* **Wrong temperature**: too low → cold joints; too high → burned pads, damaged ICs
* **Feeding solder onto the tip**: bypasses the joint; you lose flux before it can do its job
* **Ignoring polarity**: not a technique issue, but always verify component orientation before soldering

<img src="images/polarity.png" style="max-width:100%" />

<div class="warn-box">**The #1 safety mistake:** Setting the iron down on the work surface instead of returning it to the stand. Burns happen in less than a second of contact.</div>

<div class="nav-bar">[[← Previous->Reading the Joint]] [[Next: Desoldering Basics →->Desoldering Basics]]</div>


:: Desoldering Basics {"position":"400,150","size":"100,100"}
<div class="slide-label">Slide 12 of 14</div>

## Desoldering Basics

Mistakes happen. Desoldering lets you remove or rework components without damaging the board.

### Desoldering Pump (Solder Sucker)

* Spring-loaded vacuum pump: prime it, heat the joint until molten, position the tip over it, trigger
* Works best for through-hole components with larger pads
* Fast once you develop the timing; takes some practice to operate one-handed with the iron

### Desoldering Braid (Wick)

* Flux-coated copper braid: lay it over the joint, press the iron on top of the braid
* Solder wicks up into the braid via capillary action
* Excellent for cleaning up bridges and excess solder on flat pads
* Use a fresh section each time, a saturated braid won't wick

<div class="info-box">**Patience matters.** Pulling components before the solder is fully molten tears pads off the board. Let the heat do the work, not your fingers.</div>

<div class="nav-bar">[[← Previous->Common Mistakes]] [[Next: Practice & Next Steps →->Practice and Next Steps]]</div>


