:: Practice and Next Steps {"position":"525,150","size":"100,100"}
<div class="slide-label">Slide 13 of 14</div>

## Practice & Next Steps

### Building Skill

* **Start with through-hole kits**: larger pads, slower pace, easy to see what's happening. Look for beginner kits on Adafruit or SparkFun.
* **Practice boards**: dedicated boards with a variety of pad sizes and component types
* **Old/broken electronics**: great low-stakes material for desoldering practice
* **Slow down**: watch the solder flow, develop feel for heat timing, don't rush

### Good Resources

* **Adafruit Learning System** (adafruit.com/learn) — thorough beginner soldering guides with photos
* **EEVblog on YouTube**: Dave Jones' soldering tutorials are widely considered the best free resource
* **r/soldering on Reddit**: community for joint critique and technique feedback


<div class="tip-box">**Fastest way to improve:** Solder something, photograph every joint, post for critique. Specific feedback accelerates skill far faster than solo practice.</div>

<div class="nav-bar">[[← Previous->Desoldering Basics]] [[Next: Wrap-Up →->Wrap Up]]</div>


:: Preparing Your Workspace {"position":"1025,25","size":"100,100"}
<div class="slide-label">Slide 07 of 14</div>

## Preparing Your Workspace

### Physical Setup

* Work on a **heat-resistant mat**: silicone, ceramic tile, or a proper soldering mat
* Place your iron stand **within easy reach** of your dominant hand
* Ensure **good lighting**: you need to clearly see pads and component leads
* Set up **ventilation**: a fan pulling fumes away, or a dedicated fume extractor

### Before You Start Soldering

* Organize your components and PCB before turning on the iron
* Know exactly what you're going to solder and plan before you heat
* Heat the iron and **tin the tip** (covered next)
* Have your brass cleaner ready

<div class="nav-bar">[[← Previous->Soldering Iron Tips]] [[Next: Tinning the Tip →->Tinning the Tip]]</div>


:: Reading the Joint {"position":"150,150","size":"100,100"}
<div class="slide-label">Slide 10 of 14</div>

## Reading the Joint

Visually assessing a solder joint is a skill you'll develop quickly with practice.

<img src="images/common-issues.jpg" style="max-width:100%" />

### Good Joint ✅

* Smooth, shiny surface (slightly matte for lead-free — that's normal)
* Concave/volcano shape — solder wets up the component lead and down onto the pad
* You can see the outline of the pad and lead through the solder

### Cold Joint ❌

* Dull, grainy, or frosted surface
* Rounded blob that didn't wet to the pad properly
* Caused by movement during cooling, iron too cool, or insufficient heat time

### Too Much Solder ❌

* Large blob that obscures the pad and lead entirely
* Risks bridging adjacent pads → short circuit

### Solder Bridge ❌

* Solder spanning between two adjacent pads or leads
* Creates a short circuit — always inspect after soldering fine-pitch ICs

<div class="tip-box">**Use a magnifier or your phone camera** to inspect joints, especially on small components.</div>

<div class="nav-bar">[[← Previous->Basic Technique]] [[Next: Common Mistakes →->Common Mistakes]]</div>


:: Safety First {"position":"525,25","size":"100,100"}
<div class="slide-label">Slide 03 of 14</div>

## Safety First ⚠️

<div class="warn-box">**The iron tip runs at 300–400°C. (text-colour:red)+(bg:yellow)[Burns happen instantly and without warning.]**</div>

### Key Safety Rules

* **Eye protection**: always wear safety glasses
* **Ventilation**: solder fumes (flux vapor) are irritating; work near a fan or fume extractor
* **Never touch the tip**: use a stand at all times when the iron is hot
* **Lead handling**: if using leaded solder, wear gloves and wash your hands afterwards
* **Fire hazard**: keep flammables away and never leave a hot iron unattended
* **Cable management**: keep the iron cord away from the tip and your work area

<div class="tip-box">**Tip:** Return the iron to its stand between every operation. Most burns happen when an iron is set down "just for a second."</div>

<div class="nav-bar">[[← Previous->What Is Soldering]] [[Next: Tools & Materials →->Tools and Materials]]</div>


:: Soldering Iron Tips {"position":"900,25","size":"100,100"}
<div class="slide-label">Slide 06 of 14</div>

## Soldering Iron Tips

### What's in a Tip?

<img src="images/soldering-iron-tip.png" style="max-width:100%" />

### Choosing a Tip

<img src="images/soldering-iron-tip-types.png" style="max-width:100%" />

<div class="tip-box">**Tip choice:** Chisel or bevel tips transfer heat more efficiently than fine conical tips for most through-hole and pad work. Use fine tips for precision SMD work only.</div>
<div class="nav-bar">[[← Previous->The Soldering Iron]] [[Next: Preparing Your Workspace →->Preparing Your Workspace]]</div>


:: The Soldering Iron {"position":"775,25","size":"100,100"}
<div class="slide-label">Slide 05 of 14</div>

## The Soldering Iron

### Types of Irons

**Pencil iron (fixed wattage)**: Simple, inexpensive (~$15–30). Good for learning but harder to control temperature precisely.

**Temperature-controlled station**: Dial or digital setpoint. More consistent results, especially for heat-sensitive components. Recommended for regular use.

⭐ **Temperature-controlled pencil iron**: The best of both! It's simple, inexpensive (~$35). A digital setpoint and sensors provide consistent results.


### Temperature Settings

* **Leaded solder (63/37, 60/40):** 315–340°C / 600–650°F
* **Lead-free solder:** 340–370°C / 650–700°F
* **Too cool** → solder won't flow properly, cold joints
* **Too hot** → damages components, burns flux, shortens tip life

<div class="nav-bar">[[← Previous->Tools and Materials]] [[Next: Soldering Iron Tips →->Soldering Iron Tips]]</div>


:: Tinning the Tip {"position":"1150,25","size":"100,100"}
<div class="slide-label">Slide 08 of 14</div>

## Tinning the Tip

Tinning means coating the iron tip with a thin, fresh layer of solder. It is the single most important maintenance habit for clean, reliable soldering.

### Why It Matters

* A tinned (shiny, silver) tip transfers heat efficiently and wets solder properly
* An oxidized (black, dull) tip insulates itself — heat won't transfer, joints will be poor regardless of technique

### How to Tin

1. Heat the iron to working temperature
2. Clean the tip on the brass cleaner to remove old oxidation
3. Immediately touch fresh solder to the tip. It should melt and coat it evenly
4. Wipe off the excess on the cleaner, leaving a thin, shiny coat

<div class="info-box">**Tin //before// and //after// every session.** Before you put the iron away, tin it. The solder coat protects the tip from oxidizing while it cools between uses.</div>

### Keeping Tips Healthy

* Never leave a hot iron idle with a bare, dry tip for long
* Don't sand or file tips. Tt destroys the iron plating layer
* Use tip tinner/activator paste for severely oxidized tips

<div class="nav-bar">[[← Previous->Preparing Your Workspace]] [[Next: Basic Technique →->Basic Technique]]</div>


:: Title {"position":"275,25","size":"100,100"}
<div class="title-hero">

# Introduction to Soldering

<p class="subtitle">A hands-on guide to soldering electronics.</p><p class="presenter">Monty DeGauven</p>

This is a hands-on, beginner-friendly workshop. No prior experience needed, no pressure. Just a relaxed environment to try something new and build some confidence with real tools and techniques.

Today you'll learn the fundamentals of soldering while assembling a practice board with common components: resistors, capacitors, and LEDs. Everything you need is provided, and with a small group there's plenty of room for questions and one-on-one help.

Whether this is your first step into electronics or just something you've always wanted to try, you're in the right place.
</div>

<div class="nav-bar">[[Next: What Is Soldering? →->What Is Soldering]]</div>


:: Tools and Materials {"position":"650,25","size":"100,100"}
<div class="slide-label">Slide 04 of 14</div>

## Tools & Materials

### The Essentials

* **Soldering iron**: pencil-style or temperature-controlled station
* **Solder**: rosin-core, 60/40 or lead-free, 0.8mm diameter for electronics
* **Iron stand**: holds the iron safely; often includes a cleaning sponge
* **Brass tip cleaner**: removes oxidation between joints
* **Flux**: improves solder flow and wetting on difficult joints

### Helpful Extras

* **Helping hands / PCB holder**: holds your workpiece steady
* **Desoldering pump or braid**: for fixing mistakes
* **Fume extractor**: fan with filter to pull flux vapors away from your face
* **Multimeter**: verify connections electrically after soldering
* **Silicone Mat**: prevents burning work surfaces and makes cleanup easier

<div class="nav-bar">[[← Previous->Safety First]] [[Next: The Soldering Iron →->The Soldering Iron]]</div>


:: What Is Soldering {"position":"400,25","size":"100,100"}
<div class="slide-label">Slide 02 of 14</div>

## What Is Soldering?

Soldering is the process of joining two metal surfaces using a low-melting-point filler metal called solder. Unlike welding, the base materials are **not melted**, only the solder is.

### Where Is It Used?

* Electronics for circuit boards, wiring, connectors
* Plumbing to join copper pipes
* Jewelry making and metalwork
* Stained glass assembly


<div class="nav-bar">[[← Previous->Title]] [[Next: Safety First →->Safety First]]</div>


